## Introduction

Adolescence is a time of immense growth, but for many families in **Houston, Texas**, it can also be a season of hidden struggle. Imagine a teenager sitting in a high-pressure classroom at a local Houston high school, or perhaps hanging out with friends at Discovery Green, when suddenly, their heart begins to race, they can’t catch their breath, and an overwhelming sense of doom takes over. For a parent, watching your child experience this is terrifying. For the teenager, it feels like they are losing control or even dying.

This experience is often a panic attack, and when these attacks become recurrent and lead to a persistent fear of future episodes, it is classified as **Panic Disorder**. In a fast-paced metropolitan area like Houston—where academic competition is fierce and social media pressure is constant—Panic Disorder in teenagers is an increasingly common concern.

